## Security Review Summary

Reviewed: commit fbc1848 -- `review-src/handler.ts` and `review-src/validate.ts` (both new files)

### Findings

1. File: `review-src/handler.ts:6-8`
   Severity: High (confirmed)
   [A05 Security Misconfiguration]
   Unhandled `JSON.parse` at line 7 throws SyntaxError on any malformed body. Unauthenticated DoS: repeated malformed requests crash the handler frame, and in typical Node.js HTTP servers without a global error boundary this leaks stack traces or terminates the worker. Trivially exploitable with `curl -d 'x'`. Assuming no upstream Express-style error middleware (unverified), do wrap in try/catch and return 400. Verify middleware before acting.

2. File: `review-src/handler.ts:1-8` with `review-src/validate.ts:1`
   Severity: High (confirmed)
   [A04 Insecure Design]
   `validate()` is never imported; commit message "add unvalidated handler" confirms intent gap. Parsed output returned untyped to unknown downstream. Root design flaw that amplifies findings 3 and 4. Note: `validate()` itself (`x != null`) is a null-check, not structural validation -- even if wired in, it is insufficient. Do introduce a schema validator (zod/ajv) rather than wiring the existing stub.

3. File: `review-src/handler.ts:2`
   Severity: High (confirmed)
   [A04 Insecure Design]
   Truthiness guard accepts Buffers, objects, arrays. `JSON.parse(Buffer)` coerces via `toString()`, but `JSON.parse(object)` calls `String(object)` yielding `"[object Object]"` and throws -- chains into finding 1. No size cap means a multi-GB body exhausts memory before parse. Exploitable pre-auth.

4. File: `review-src/handler.ts:7`
   Severity: Medium (confirmed; latent)
   [A08 Software and Data Integrity Failures]
   `JSON.parse` itself does set `__proto__` as an own property (not polluting), but downstream merges (`Object.assign`, spread) propagate it. Severity is latent because blast radius depends on unseen consumers. Assuming consumers merge the result into config/session objects (unverified), do use `JSON.parse(data, (k,v) => k==='__proto__' ? undefined : v)` or a schema allowlist. Verify consumer code before acting.

### Threat Patterns

Findings 1, 2, and 3 form a single-request unauthenticated DoS chain: no auth gate (implied by absent auth code) -> weak truthiness check (F3) lets oversized/wrong-type bodies through -> `JSON.parse` throws (F1) because no validator intercepts (F2) -> process error propagates. One `curl` with a 500MB malformed payload exercises all three.

Findings 2 and 4 form a latent integrity chain: the missing validation layer (F2) is the root cause that leaves F4's prototype-pollution surface exposed. Wiring a real schema validator closes both simultaneously; wiring the existing `validate()` stub closes neither.

Shared root cause across all four findings: the handler treats the HTTP boundary as trusted. A single schema-validation layer (zod/ajv) with body-size middleware and a try/catch boundary resolves findings 1-4 together. Adjacent surface not scanned: the HTTP framework's body parser configuration (size limits, content-type enforcement) and any global error handler -- both materially change exploitability of finding 1.
